sources.about:
The Indian Nursing Council is a national regulatory body for nurses and nurse education in India.
It is an autonomous body under the Government of India, Ministry of Health & Family Welfare, constituted by the Central Government under section 3(1) of the Indian Nursing Council Act, 1947 of Indian parliament.Indian Nursing Council is the apex body that establishes Uniforms Standards of Training for Nurses, Midwives and Health Visitors
sources.Purposes:
Indian Nursing Council with the support of the Maternity Foundation brings an E-Learning Platform with an aim to improve the knowledge and confidence of the existing and upcoming nursing workforce in midwifery/nursing by implementing EdTech tool in various curriculum/program offered and implemented by INC.
This Online Learning is an experience that goes above and beyond basic Classroom-based sessions.
sources.Audience: This E-Learning platform is for the entire nursing audience which includes practitioners, nurse managers/leaders, nursing faculty and students.

Jhpiego is a nonprofit global health leader and Johns Hopkins University affiliate that saves lives, improves health and transforms futures.

Jhpiego translates the best science and practice into moments of care that can make the difference between life and death for women and families.

Jhpiego partners with national governments, health experts, local communities, and the private sector to build the skills and systems that guarantee a healthier future for women and families. Through these partnerships, Jhpiego is revolutionizing health care for the world's most disadvantaged and vulnerable people.

In India, Jhpiego has an active presence in 28 states, 2 union territories and 700+ districts. Jhpiego works in close collaboration with national and state governments, providing technical and strategic assistance in the areas of family planning and reproductive health, maternal and child health, strengthening human resources for health, strengthening health systems for comprehensive primary healthcare and responding to health emergencies, women's cancer, infectious diseases, immunization, gender, climate and health, digital health, and non-communicable diseases.
